"prob": 0.9706756472587585, "span": {"begin": 2052, "end": 2056}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1588"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "aromatase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9633716940879822, "span": {"begin": 2117, "end": 2126}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004051"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DEHP", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9962695837020874, "span": {"begin": 2153, "end": 2157}}, {"id": ["mesh:C016599"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MEHP", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9979259371757507, "span": {"begin": 2178, "end": 2182}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1588"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Aromatase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9689688086509705, "span": {"begin": 2206, "end": 2215}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004051"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DEHP", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9826871752738953, "span": {"begin": 2223, "end": 2227}}, {"id": ["mesh:C016599"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MEHP", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9545714855194092, "span": {"begin": 2245, "end": 2249}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1588"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "aromatase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.985343873500824, "span": {"begin": 2346, "end": 2355}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1588"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "aromatase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.976751983165741, "span": {"begin": 2371, "end": 2380}}], "text": "Environmental agents, toxicants, and various natural products can impact on aromatase activity and/or alteration in protein levels to result in reduced levels of estrogen.   Studies providing evidence for the linkage of aromatase decrease and decreased E2 production include: Bisphenol A: in vitro, human: significant reduction of aromatase from 40M and decreased E2 production from 80 M (Kwintkiewicz, Nishi, Yanase, &amp; Giudice, 2010) at the same time point. MEHP, in vitro:   human, from 10M decreased aromatase activity (dose dependent), at 167 M decrease in mRNA levels of aromatase and from 10M decrease of estradiol production (dose dependent), measured at the same time point (48h) (Reinsberg, Wegener-Toper, van der Ven, van der Ven, &amp; Klingmueller, 2009)  rat, dose response decrease in aromatase levels from 50M, dose dependent decrease of E2 production from 100M, at the same (48 h) (Lovekamp &amp; Davis, 2001).  rat, decrease in aromatase levels at 100g/ml DEHP, 10g/ml MEHP and dose dependent  decrease of E2 production from 10g/ml DEHP, 0.1g/ml MEHP and at the same time point (96 h) (Gupta et al., 2010). Table 1 summarises available empirical evidence.       Compound    Species   Study type   comments   Aromatase decrease levels/activity   Reference    MEHP    rat    in vitro   decrease activity of aromatase and dose and time dependent decrease of E2 production   decrease activity of aromatase 100 M E2 production 50-100 M   (Davis, Weaver, Gaines, &amp; Heindel, 1994),    MEHP    rat    ex vivo   decrease aromatase level and dose decrease of E2 production   aromatase level 50M E2 production 100-200 M   (Lovekamp &amp; Davis, 2001)     DEHP    rat   in vivo   Does dependent reduction of  E2 levels, and Does dependent reduction decrease aromatase expression   300-600mg/kg/day   (Xu et al., 2010),    MEHP    human   in vitro   Dose dependent reduction E2 production and reduction aromatase of expression   reduction E2 levels IC(50)= 49- 138 M, at 167M decrease aromatase    (Reinsberg et al., 2009)    MEHP/DEHP     mice   ex vivo   dose dependent E2 production, and reduction  of aromatase levels   E2 production at DEHP (10 -100&#160;g/ml);MEHP (0.1 and 10&#160;g/ml) Aromatase levels DEHP (100&#160;g/ml); MEHP 0.1&#160;g/ml   (Gupta et al., 2010)  This KE describes decreased levels and/or availability of aromatase different from aromatase inhibition.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:22:34 +0000 2026"}